WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:03.436 --> 00:00:04.737 align:start size:84% position:16%
Dana Frayne: Go
ahead and get started.

00:00:04.770 --> 00:00:07.640 align:start size:84% position:16%
So before we dive
in, thank you, Amber,

00:00:07.673 --> 00:00:09.308
for that wonderful introduction.

00:00:09.341 --> 00:00:13.646 align:start position:0%
I also just want to give a
little background as well about

00:00:13.679 --> 00:00:16.716 align:start size:88% position:13%
who I am and why I'll be
talking about what

00:00:16.749 --> 00:00:18.217
I'm talking about today.

00:00:18.250 --> 00:00:20.720
So my name is Dana Frayne.

00:00:20.753 --> 00:00:25.058 align:start position:0%
I'm at the University of
Oxford as a master's student and

00:00:25.091 --> 00:00:29.829 align:start position:0%
specifically I'm at the Internet
Institute so I spend my days

00:00:29.862 --> 00:00:34.333
thinking about how the Internet
essentially affects society,

00:00:34.366 --> 00:00:37.403 align:start size:94% position:6%
particularly in relation to
how the Internet

00:00:37.436 --> 00:00:39.739
is accessible online.

00:00:39.772 --> 00:00:43.409 align:start position:0%
Before coming to Oxford, I
was already quite interested in

00:00:43.442 --> 00:00:47.280 align:start position:0%
digital accessibility so I don't
think it surprised any of my

00:00:47.313 --> 00:00:51.884
friends or people who know me
that I wanted to study this for

00:00:51.917 --> 00:00:54.287
my master's thesis.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:58.191
In particular, like Amber said,
I worked as a freelance digital

00:00:58.224 --> 00:01:03.463 align:start position:0%
accessibility consultant and one
of my projects working on the

00:01:03.496 --> 00:01:08.301
American Civil Liberty--Civil
Liberties Union home page so

00:01:08.334 --> 00:01:10.470 align:start size:94% position:6%
that it was
accessible was really great.

00:01:10.503 --> 00:01:15.041
So currently finishing up the
master's degree at Oxford and

00:01:15.074 --> 00:01:18.478
I'm gonna be talking about some
of my thesis findings today as

00:01:18.511 --> 00:01:22.849
well as, you know, some of my
personal experiences working

00:01:22.882 --> 00:01:25.151
in digital accessibility.

00:01:25.184 --> 00:01:30.089
So, as sort of the agenda for
the talk today, first I'm gonna

00:01:30.122 --> 00:01:33.759
kind of give a overview of
my research goals and then

00:01:33.792 --> 00:01:38.831 align:start position:0%
transition to a brief discussion
of the theoretical frameworks

00:01:38.864 --> 00:01:41.400 align:start size:84% position:16%
that are kind of
driving that question.

00:01:41.433 --> 00:01:45.505
Then I'm going to be examining
briefly the method I use and

00:01:45.538 --> 00:01:51.277 align:start size:84% position:16%
then the findings
and future directions.

00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:55.748 align:start position:0%
So, the main takeaway from my
background earlier, is that I am

00:01:55.781 --> 00:02:00.520 align:start position:0%
coming from both a practical
perspective on one side but then

00:02:00.553 --> 00:02:05.625
also theoretical, more academic,
perspective and I mentioned my

00:02:05.658 --> 00:02:10.062
course work at Oxford and that
involves a thesis which, one of

00:02:10.095 --> 00:02:14.467
the main requirements is having
a research question, so on the

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:19.505 align:start size:97% position:3%
screen now is mine which says:
"What is the role of social

00:02:19.538 --> 00:02:24.210
norms in the implementation of
digital accessibility practices

00:02:24.243 --> 00:02:26.412
in the technology industry?"

00:02:26.445 --> 00:02:31.083 align:start size:97% position:3%
So, with this question, I
was essentially working toward

00:02:31.116 --> 00:02:35.254
figuring out and observing the
different norms that operate

00:02:35.287 --> 00:02:37.823 align:start size:78% position:22%
when people
are trying to put

00:02:37.856 --> 00:02:43.262 align:start size:97% position:3%
digital accessibility policies
into practice.

00:02:43.295 --> 00:02:48.834 align:start position:0%
So one question I got in is
why study this particular topic?

00:02:48.867 --> 00:02:54.340
And there are a few reasons,
the first one being that I have

00:02:54.373 --> 00:02:58.277
found there is a gap in the
academic literature regarding

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:03.149 align:start position:0%
social norms and digital
accessibility, partially because

00:03:03.182 --> 00:03:07.687
there is not, I'd say, a great
deal of academic research that,

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:11.324
you know, sort of publicly
exists squarely on the topic

00:03:11.357 --> 00:03:13.693
of digital accessibility.

00:03:13.726 --> 00:03:18.197
You know, furthermore, the
research that does exist is

00:03:18.230 --> 00:03:24.537
often--it can be siloed into
niche topics and circles so

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:29.308
sometimes there is a risk of
being sort of put into echo

00:03:29.341 --> 00:03:33.045 align:start size:97% position:3%
chambers of people who already
feel quite strongly about

00:03:33.078 --> 00:03:37.383
digital accessibility, and then
you know, for the research that

00:03:37.416 --> 00:03:41.254
does exist, the data does not
always, you know, cover the

00:03:41.287 --> 00:03:45.424 align:start size:97% position:3%
aspect of implementation so
particularly in the technology

00:03:45.457 --> 00:03:50.062
industry, sometimes I've found
that the viewpoints can be a bit

00:03:50.095 --> 00:03:54.834 align:start position:0%
disconnected between, you
know, industry versus academia.

00:03:54.867 --> 00:03:57.737
So one of the goals of my
research is to sort of, you

00:03:57.770 --> 00:04:03.776
know, merge these two viewpoints
together, not that they exist,

00:04:03.809 --> 00:04:08.047
you know, completely separately
but that was one of the goals.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:12.785
And then, you know, secondly, or
second, digital accessibility is

00:04:12.818 --> 00:04:17.123
highly, highly interdisciplinary
which I'm sure a lot of people

00:04:17.156 --> 00:04:22.695
tuning in can relate to this
idea that, you know, to work in

00:04:22.728 --> 00:04:26.799
digital accessibility sometimes
it feels like, you know, you

00:04:26.832 --> 00:04:29.735 align:start position:0%
specialize in a lot of different
areas from, you know, the

00:04:29.768 --> 00:04:33.539
technical part to the legal part
to, you know, the theory part,

00:04:33.572 --> 00:04:35.508
and there are lots of
different parts to it.

00:04:35.541 --> 00:04:41.480
So I--that was another reason I
wanted to kind of address social

00:04:41.513 --> 00:04:44.750
norms because they touch on,
you know, all those areas.

00:04:44.783 --> 00:04:49.221 align:start position:0%
And then finally, the third
reason which is the main reason

00:04:49.254 --> 00:04:54.193
I wanted to study this is,
you know, my main personal

00:04:54.226 --> 00:04:57.330 align:start size:94% position:6%
experiences with digital
accessibility and working in

00:04:57.363 --> 00:05:01.367
digital accessibility, I
feel like I have, you know,

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:04.103
personally experienced these
social norms that I'm going to

00:05:04.136 --> 00:05:09.608 align:start position:0%
talk about and my hope in
bringing them up today is that,

00:05:09.641 --> 00:05:14.013 align:start position:0%
you know, maybe, you know,
someone tuning in will also have

00:05:14.046 --> 00:05:18.484
experienced this and I think, as
a community of people who care

00:05:18.517 --> 00:05:22.188
about digital accessibility,
it's important to, you know,

00:05:22.221 --> 00:05:27.493 align:start size:91% position:9%
kind of rally around, you
know, advocating

00:05:27.526 --> 00:05:29.795
for digital accessibility.

00:05:29.828 --> 00:05:34.467 align:start position:0%
So, that's kind of the goal with
my research and the goal that

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:40.473
I'm--that I have today and I
think that's partially why

00:05:40.506 --> 00:05:42.842
events like these are so
great because it brings

00:05:42.875 --> 00:05:45.244
the community together.

00:05:45.277 --> 00:05:51.817
So, moving on into the research
itself, I'm not going to spend a

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:56.055 align:start position:0%
great deal of time defining
theories and frameworks but I've

00:05:56.088 --> 00:06:02.495
included the major theorist in
parentheses here on the screen,

00:06:02.528 --> 00:06:06.298 align:start size:91% position:9%
along with, you know,
their associated theories.

00:06:06.331 --> 00:06:09.635 align:start position:0%
So if you're interested and
wanna learn more about anything

00:06:09.668 --> 00:06:13.639
I'm talking about, I have a list
of references at the end if you

00:06:13.672 --> 00:06:17.610
wanna check it--check out
these theories further.

00:06:17.643 --> 00:06:22.114 align:start size:97% position:3%
But the first one says the
social model of disability and

00:06:22.147 --> 00:06:25.518 align:start position:0%
Mike Oliver and Tom Shakespeare
are two of the, you know,

00:06:25.551 --> 00:06:28.320
leading architects
of this framework.

00:06:28.353 --> 00:06:32.658
And it has its foundations in
the United Kingdom, sort of the

00:06:32.691 --> 00:06:37.329
activist grassroots movement
when there was a big push from

00:06:37.362 --> 00:06:41.700 align:start position:0%
the medical model of
disability to the social model.

00:06:41.733 --> 00:06:45.671
And the conception of the social
model was, you know, founded in

00:06:45.704 --> 00:06:50.376 align:start size:97% position:3%
this idea that social barriers
blocked participation

00:06:50.409 --> 00:06:51.577
in social groups.

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:58.150 align:start size:97% position:3%
So this is a problem because,
you know, this, you know,

00:06:58.183 --> 00:07:00.619
potentially could lead to
obstacles for people with

00:07:00.652 --> 00:07:03.122
disabilities to
lead a fulfilling

00:07:03.155 --> 00:07:05.424
and high quality of life.

00:07:05.457 --> 00:07:09.094 align:start size:97% position:3%
And I mention this here,
primarily, because the social

00:07:09.127 --> 00:07:14.767
model is now the primary mode
in which scholars studying the

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:19.338
topic of disability utilize and
it's therefore, you know, the

00:07:19.371 --> 00:07:22.775
model that drives this research.

00:07:22.808 --> 00:07:25.711
Just gonna take a
sip real quick.

00:07:27.579 --> 00:07:32.151
Okay, well, so, moving on to
the next theory I have listed.

00:07:32.184 --> 00:07:36.622
So, intersectionality from
Kimberlé Crenshaw who is a

00:07:36.655 --> 00:07:38.624
brilliant feminist scholar.

00:07:38.657 --> 00:07:42.661
She, you know, coined and is one
of the lead architects of this

00:07:42.694 --> 00:07:47.366
concept, intersectionality,
which essentially means the

00:07:47.399 --> 00:07:51.570
aspects of identity are fluid as
opposed to concrete, you know,

00:07:51.603 --> 00:07:56.842
single artifacts of one's
self and self-presentation.

00:07:56.875 --> 00:08:01.780
And in other words, you know,
intersectionality is sort of

00:08:01.813 --> 00:08:06.252 align:start size:97% position:3%
this idea that multiple
identities like--dimensions of

00:08:06.285 --> 00:08:10.523 align:start size:97% position:3%
identity like race,
socioeconomic status, gender,

00:08:10.556 --> 00:08:15.794
ability, you know, so on, they
deserve an equitable weight when

00:08:15.827 --> 00:08:19.698
kind of considering
identity politics.

00:08:19.731 --> 00:08:26.038
So, based on this, you know,
cornerstone theory, it's--I'd

00:08:26.071 --> 00:08:29.808
say it's fair to suggest that
disability is intertwined with,

00:08:29.841 --> 00:08:34.113
you know, a lot of different
dimensions of identity, so when

00:08:34.146 --> 00:08:37.316
talking about this research, I
feel like it's really important

00:08:37.349 --> 00:08:42.788
to acknowledge that, you know,
disability doesn't, you know,

00:08:42.821 --> 00:08:47.226
essentially exist in a vacuum.

00:08:47.259 --> 00:08:50.362
It's, you know, there are lots
of parts of identity to think

00:08:50.395 --> 00:08:56.368
about so I just wanna note up
front that I try to, you know,

00:08:56.401 --> 00:09:00.239 align:start size:97% position:3%
incorporate intersectionality
into my research and just

00:09:00.272 --> 00:09:02.575
general life approach.

00:09:02.608 --> 00:09:07.279
And then, you know, moving
on to the next framework, the

00:09:07.312 --> 00:09:11.984
narrative self, which is
proposed by and, you know,

00:09:12.017 --> 00:09:17.189
really led by this philosopher
named Marya Schechtman and, you

00:09:17.222 --> 00:09:23.429
know, essentially the narrative
self presents this idea that a

00:09:23.462 --> 00:09:27.266
cohesive collection of one's
memories and ideas about the

00:09:27.299 --> 00:09:33.772
self come together to present,
you know, the self presentation

00:09:33.805 --> 00:09:39.445
so, in other words, whenever I
hear someone say, "This is, you

00:09:39.478 --> 00:09:43.482
know, on brand for this person,"
I sort of think of this theory

00:09:43.515 --> 00:09:49.688
because it's essentially, you
know, Schechtman's idea that,

00:09:49.721 --> 00:09:54.660
you know, presentations of
the self, you know, it's a

00:09:54.693 --> 00:09:57.463
collection of different
memories and artifacts

00:09:57.496 --> 00:09:59.164
that are shared online.

00:09:59.197 --> 00:10:04.670 align:start position:0%
So, with these theories in
mind, I'm gonna transition to a

00:10:04.703 --> 00:10:09.842 align:start size:91% position:9%
discussion of the findings
and the process

00:10:09.875 --> 00:10:11.510
of gathering the findings.

00:10:11.543 --> 00:10:17.483
So for my thesis, I conducted
a series of interviews with

00:10:17.516 --> 00:10:21.520 align:start position:0%
accessibility experts and
practitioners and it's important

00:10:21.553 --> 00:10:26.158 align:start size:97% position:3%
to note that the primary
framework that I used was the

00:10:26.191 --> 00:10:32.164 align:start position:0%
postmodernist viewpoint because
it was really, you know, I

00:10:32.197 --> 00:10:35.834
related to it a lot because it
emphasized the nuanced nature

00:10:35.867 --> 00:10:39.505 align:start position:0%
of, you know, the
interviewer and the interviewee

00:10:39.538 --> 00:10:43.709
relationship, along with the
broader philosophical belief

00:10:43.742 --> 00:10:46.512 align:start size:88% position:13%
that, you know, multiple
versions of the truth

00:10:46.545 --> 00:10:49.848
can exist in society.

00:10:49.881 --> 00:10:54.353
Also I was conscientious about
the broader postmodernist push

00:10:54.386 --> 00:10:58.624 align:start size:94% position:6%
in academia to adhere to
equitable sampling practices

00:10:58.657 --> 00:11:01.727 align:start size:94% position:6%
in order to better represent
diverse experiences

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.662
in the findings.

00:11:03.695 --> 00:11:08.567
I'm just gonna--okay, sorry.

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:11.403 align:start size:97% position:3%
I feel like I'm battling a bit
of a cold coming on,

00:11:11.436 --> 00:11:15.040
so, sorry about that.

00:11:15.073 --> 00:11:16.308
Okay, back to it.

00:11:16.341 --> 00:11:24.516
So, the second point was that
just another, you know, minor

00:11:24.549 --> 00:11:29.154
know is that one of my concerns
with the interview method was

00:11:29.187 --> 00:11:34.326
sometimes people can say, you
know, interviews purely produce

00:11:34.359 --> 00:11:38.664
descriptive findings but, you
know, I would kind of push back

00:11:38.697 --> 00:11:42.434 align:start position:0%
against this idea in the
sense that it's--interviews are

00:11:42.467 --> 00:11:49.341 align:start position:0%
useful, particularly in
sociological research to uncover

00:11:49.374 --> 00:11:52.344
social norms and
some perspectives

00:11:52.377 --> 00:11:56.215
that can sometimes be hidden.

00:11:56.248 --> 00:12:00.519 align:start position:0%
So now I'm gonna shift to a
discussion of the findings and,

00:12:00.552 --> 00:12:07.326
to do that, I am going to
read off a brief scenario.

00:12:09.528 --> 00:12:15.334
Okay, so, the--I'm gonna
read what's onscreen now.

00:12:15.367 --> 00:12:19.037 line:0%
So, imagine that you're working
at a company that is launching a

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:20.305 line:0%
new website tomorrow.

00:12:20.338 --> 00:12:23.742 line:0%
You primarily work as a product
designer, but you're considered

00:12:23.775 --> 00:12:27.846 line:0%
the "go-to" person for digital
accessibility in the company.

00:12:27.879 --> 00:12:30.816 line:0%
You don't personally work on
the team that's preparing for

00:12:30.849 --> 00:12:34.520 line:0%
launch, but a manager from a
different team knows that you

00:12:34.553 --> 00:12:37.089 line:0%
know a lot about accessibility.

00:12:37.122 --> 00:12:39.825 line:0%
This manager emails
you to ask, "Hey!

00:12:39.858 --> 00:12:42.828 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
Can you make the
website accessible before

00:12:42.861 --> 00:12:45.264 line:0%
the launch tomorrow?"

00:12:45.297 --> 00:12:48.333 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
Less than a day is not a
lot of time to make a website

00:12:48.366 --> 00:12:51.703 line:0%
accessible, but you really want
to help because no one else in

00:12:51.736 --> 00:12:55.340 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
the company seems to
know about

00:12:55.373 --> 00:12:57.676 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
the specific accessibility
guidelines.

00:12:57.709 --> 00:13:01.780 line:0%
So you ask the manager, "Sure,
but, you know, what has already

00:13:01.813 --> 00:13:04.349 line:0%
been done for accessibility?"

00:13:04.382 --> 00:13:08.320 line:0%
They respond by saying, "We only
just remembered because we don't

00:13:08.353 --> 00:13:11.323 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
want to get in trouble
with an inaccessible site.

00:13:11.356 --> 00:13:14.126 line:0%
If you could just check
the boxes for the basic

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:18.163 line:0%
accessibility criteria before
launch, that would be great!"

00:13:18.196 --> 00:13:22.668 align:start size:91% position:9% line:0%
Okay, so let's
dissect this for a moment.

00:13:22.701 --> 00:13:26.572 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
You know, I cannot see the
comments right now but I would

00:13:26.605 --> 00:13:30.809 align:start position:0% line:0%
venture to ask if anyone
listening or, you know, watching

00:13:30.842 --> 00:13:34.246 line:0%
has ever experienced a
scenario similar to this.

00:13:34.279 --> 00:13:36.748 line:0%
I know bits and pieces of this.

00:13:36.781 --> 00:13:41.153 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
I certainly have, but
essentially I wanted to share

00:13:41.186 --> 00:13:46.225 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
this, you know, fictional
scenario that's sort of drawn

00:13:46.258 --> 00:13:51.363 line:0%
from some truths that I, you
know, experienced because it

00:13:51.396 --> 00:13:54.166 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
represents all three of
the social norms

00:13:54.199 --> 00:13:56.869 line:0%
that I'm gonna talk about today.

00:13:56.902 --> 00:14:02.274
So, the three social norms have,
like I mentioned in the agenda,

00:14:02.307 --> 00:14:07.346 align:start position:0%
are--so the first one's
compliance culture which I think

00:14:07.379 --> 00:14:09.448 align:start size:88% position:13%
hopefully a lot of
people find interesting.

00:14:09.481 --> 00:14:14.720 align:start position:0%
And then the second one is
valuation of accessibility work

00:14:14.753 --> 00:14:19.391
and then the third one is
educational opportunities.

00:14:19.424 --> 00:14:23.128
So now I'm going to transition
into a discussion of each of

00:14:23.161 --> 00:14:29.801
these social norms by talking
about what they are, how they

00:14:29.834 --> 00:14:32.471 align:start size:84% position:16%
play a role in digital
accessibility,

00:14:32.504 --> 00:14:36.074
and then why they exist.

00:14:36.107 --> 00:14:38.477
So, first, compliance culture.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:43.081 align:start size:91% position:9%
In relation to digital
accessibility is a concept

00:14:43.114 --> 00:14:46.151 align:start size:88% position:13%
that's discussed a great
deal in actually

00:14:46.184 --> 00:14:48.654 align:start size:84% position:16%
Professor Sarah
Lewthwaite's research.

00:14:48.687 --> 00:14:52.391 align:start size:88% position:13%
She focuses on studying
the pedagogy

00:14:52.424 --> 00:14:54.159
of digital accessibility.

00:14:54.192 --> 00:14:57.529
So her research is really
fascinating and if you're

00:14:57.562 --> 00:14:59.998
interested in learning more
about compliance culture, I

00:15:00.031 --> 00:15:04.436 align:start position:0%
would definitely recommend
looking up some of her articles.

00:15:04.469 --> 00:15:07.439 align:start size:97% position:3%
Or you can email me afterwards
and I can, you know,

00:15:07.472 --> 00:15:09.441
send you some as well.

00:15:09.474 --> 00:15:14.279 align:start size:97% position:3%
But anyways, you know, as a
concept, compliance culture is

00:15:14.312 --> 00:15:18.116 align:start size:97% position:3%
this idea that digital
accessibility is only a set of

00:15:18.149 --> 00:15:23.221
rules to abide by as opposed to
a genuine, you know, approach to

00:15:23.254 --> 00:15:29.828
accessibility that reinforces
creativity and continuity.

00:15:29.861 --> 00:15:33.065
And I, you know, I also wanna
note here before moving forward

00:15:33.098 --> 00:15:38.070
that just the name itself,
compliance culture, you know,

00:15:38.103 --> 00:15:41.707
can potentially be misleading
in the sense, you know, when I

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:47.646 align:start position:0%
first heard about it, I was a
bit confused because on its own,

00:15:47.679 --> 00:15:51.183 align:start position:0%
you know, I'd argue that
compliance is a good thing, you

00:15:51.216 --> 00:15:55.053
know, complying with policies
shows that, you know, people

00:15:55.086 --> 00:16:01.259
care, but, you know, the main
difference between compliance

00:16:01.292 --> 00:16:05.497
versus compliance culture is,
you know, it graduates from

00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:10.435
being this, you know, practice
to, you know, an attitude and

00:16:10.468 --> 00:16:15.107 align:start position:0%
set of behaviors making it
more aligned with a social norm.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:21.046
So that's when it becomes more
of an issue and this relates to

00:16:21.079 --> 00:16:26.018
digital accessibility because,
you know, in interviews with

00:16:26.051 --> 00:16:29.121 align:start size:94% position:6%
digital accessibility
practitioners working in the

00:16:29.154 --> 00:16:33.692
technology industry, there was
this repeated theme about the

00:16:33.725 --> 00:16:38.530 align:start position:0%
ongoing effort to kind of stymie
the practices of compliance

00:16:38.563 --> 00:16:45.370
culture because, you know,
compliance culture can block,

00:16:45.403 --> 00:16:48.340
you know, sustainability
of continued accessibility

00:16:48.373 --> 00:16:54.479
practices, particularly because
it can sort of stand as a road

00:16:54.512 --> 00:16:59.518 align:start size:97% position:3%
block between working
towards, you know, creativity,

00:16:59.551 --> 00:17:03.288 align:start position:0%
innovation, and you know,
continuous accessibility process

00:17:03.321 --> 00:17:08.326 align:start size:94% position:6%
as opposed to this
static, rigid, set of rules.

00:17:08.359 --> 00:17:14.266
So, going back to the scenario I
presented, I wanted to highlight

00:17:14.299 --> 00:17:20.172 align:start size:97% position:3%
this particular part that
sort of exemplifies this idea.

00:17:20.205 --> 00:17:26.111
So on the screen it says the
quote, "We only just remembered

00:17:26.144 --> 00:17:28.180 align:start size:84% position:16%
because we don't want
to get in trouble

00:17:28.213 --> 00:17:29.514
with an inaccessible site."

00:17:29.547 --> 00:17:32.517 align:start size:94% position:6%
This is coming from the
perspective of the manager.

00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:35.687
"If you could just check
the boxes for the basic

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:39.825
accessibility criteria before
launch, that would be great."

00:17:39.858 --> 00:17:45.831 align:start position:0%
So, this certainly has elements
of compliance culture,

00:17:45.864 --> 00:17:49.568
in particular there's
the sense of urgency.

00:17:49.601 --> 00:17:51.837
"We only just remembered."

00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:55.841 align:start size:97% position:3%
This is a problem because
accessibility should certainly

00:17:55.874 --> 00:18:01.413
be a--in an ideal world,
accessibility should be

00:18:01.446 --> 00:18:04.449
incorporated from the very
beginning of the product

00:18:04.482 --> 00:18:08.186
development process for, you
know, a multitude of reasons,

00:18:08.219 --> 00:18:13.091
but in particular, you know,
one of those reasons is that it

00:18:13.124 --> 00:18:17.762 align:start size:97% position:3%
prevents sort of this
last-minute stressful time of

00:18:17.795 --> 00:18:21.600 align:start position:0%
trying to make something
accessible really quick because

00:18:21.633 --> 00:18:27.472
it sort of changes from this,
you know, process of, okay, how

00:18:27.505 --> 00:18:32.777
can we make this user experience
a good one as opposed to, okay,

00:18:32.810 --> 00:18:37.315 align:start size:97% position:3%
how can we quickly just,
you know, meet the very basic

00:18:37.348 --> 00:18:41.286
accessibility criteria so
we don't get in trouble.?

00:18:41.319 --> 00:18:44.222 align:start position:0%
You know, those are two
different--there are significant

00:18:44.255 --> 00:18:48.460 align:start size:94% position:6%
differences bet those two
approaches, and it's sort of

00:18:48.493 --> 00:18:51.830 align:start size:94% position:6%
where compliance
culture is really relevant.

00:18:51.863 --> 00:18:57.068
So before moving on to the next
social norm, I just wanted to

00:18:57.101 --> 00:19:01.740
take a moment to reflect on, you
know, some reasons why I think

00:19:01.773 --> 00:19:06.444 align:start size:97% position:3%
compliance culture exists
and regarding the theoretical

00:19:06.477 --> 00:19:11.149 align:start size:97% position:3%
concerns, I think this
represents sort of a quick fix

00:19:11.182 --> 00:19:16.021 align:start position:0%
mentality in the technology
industry because, you know, from

00:19:16.054 --> 00:19:24.262 align:start size:97% position:3%
my experience--from my
experience working in tech, I

00:19:24.295 --> 00:19:29.434
have found that, you know, there
are, you know, pressures to work

00:19:29.467 --> 00:19:32.470 align:start size:84% position:16%
quickly and
launch things quickly.

00:19:32.503 --> 00:19:39.277
And, you know, I think that's
good for, you know, innovation.

00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:44.816
However, I think in order for
accessibility to, you know,

00:19:44.849 --> 00:19:50.455
exist in that sort of very fast
process, it's essential that

00:19:50.488 --> 00:19:55.627
it's ongoing consideration as
opposed to, okay, let's look at

00:19:55.660 --> 00:19:58.363
this right before we launch.

00:19:58.396 --> 00:20:02.234
And then, another--something
also that, you know, I've been

00:20:02.267 --> 00:20:07.405
thinking about, and some other
scholars in this space, like

00:20:07.438 --> 00:20:11.810 align:start position:0%
Professor -- and
Professor Sarah Lewthwaite also

00:20:11.843 --> 00:20:14.246 align:start size:97% position:3%
have, you know, produced
research on, also other great

00:20:14.279 --> 00:20:19.718
scholars, but essentially
there's this debate where

00:20:19.751 --> 00:20:23.555
sometimes the definitions of
accessibility, the policies of

00:20:23.588 --> 00:20:26.324 align:start size:81% position:19%
accessibility,
can be quite broad.

00:20:26.357 --> 00:20:31.496 align:start size:97% position:3%
So sometimes it can feel
difficult to know exactly what

00:20:31.529 --> 00:20:37.335 align:start size:97% position:3%
to do in order to make this
something accessible, when if,

00:20:37.368 --> 00:20:40.739
you know, someone doesn't
know how to make something

00:20:40.772 --> 00:20:45.543 align:start position:0%
accessible, which I talk further
about in the upcoming norms.

00:20:45.576 --> 00:20:50.749
And then, the last two points:
practical constraints, so again,

00:20:50.782 --> 00:20:53.752
time constraints are a
consideration, and the

00:20:53.785 --> 00:20:55.587
availability of resources.

00:20:55.620 --> 00:21:03.295
So, again with this scenario,
this scenario presented, you

00:21:03.328 --> 00:21:06.498 align:start size:97% position:3%
know, trying to make something
accessible in a very short

00:21:06.531 --> 00:21:12.037
amount of time and there's,
you know, putting all the

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:15.373 align:start position:0%
responsibility on one
person, can be quite difficult.

00:21:15.406 --> 00:21:18.343 align:start position:0%
You know, the scenario didn't
mention how, you know, expansive

00:21:18.376 --> 00:21:23.315
the product was so that can
again be quite challenging.

00:21:23.348 --> 00:21:24.716
So, moving on to

00:21:24.749 --> 00:21:27.719
the next --
social norm.

00:21:27.752 --> 00:21:31.823 align:start size:91% position:9%
I wanted to talk about
the attitude and behaviors

00:21:31.856 --> 00:21:36.528
associated with the valuation
of digital accessibility work.

00:21:36.561 --> 00:21:40.598
And here, I wanna kind
of pause for clarity.

00:21:40.631 --> 00:21:47.105 align:start position:0%
When I say, "valuation," I am
talking about both the financial

00:21:47.138 --> 00:21:50.675
and opportunity cost
associated with the

00:21:50.708 --> 00:21:53.345
work of digital accessibility.

00:21:53.378 --> 00:21:58.550
So, the first point I want to
address is that the values

00:21:58.583 --> 00:22:02.787
associated with this digital
accessibility work are quite

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:09.661 align:start position:0%
varied, you know, based on
industry and location and a lot

00:22:09.694 --> 00:22:15.367
of different factors, and also,
you know, going back to, you

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:18.303
know, Kimberlé Crenshaw's theory
of intersectionality, there are

00:22:18.336 --> 00:22:26.378
a lot of factors at play with
cost and value, so it's--so I

00:22:26.411 --> 00:22:28.646 align:start size:91% position:9%
wanna make sure I clarify
here that, you know,

00:22:28.679 --> 00:22:31.149
it doesn't exist in a vacuum.

00:22:31.182 --> 00:22:36.721
However, there is this trend
I noticed in my research and

00:22:36.754 --> 00:22:41.493
personal experience that
this, you know, it is not

00:22:41.526 --> 00:22:47.499
always--accessibility work
is not always, you know,

00:22:47.532 --> 00:22:52.370
compensated fairly in my opinion
and, you know, one of the most

00:22:52.403 --> 00:22:58.777 align:start position:0%
common ways that this manifests
is and maybe some people

00:22:58.810 --> 00:23:04.182
watching or listening have had
this experience where people who

00:23:04.215 --> 00:23:07.452 align:start position:0%
are, you know, experts or
knowledgeable, even, in digital

00:23:07.485 --> 00:23:12.323
accessibility practices are
called on to do the work of

00:23:12.356 --> 00:23:17.295
multiple people and so, by this,
I mean that sometimes, digital

00:23:17.328 --> 00:23:23.334 align:start position:0%
accessibility is sort of viewed
as maybe a side project or

00:23:23.367 --> 00:23:28.573
optional and, you know, in this
scenario, you know, this person

00:23:28.606 --> 00:23:32.544 align:start size:97% position:3%
is sort of--it's not clear
whether this person's going to

00:23:32.577 --> 00:23:35.680 align:start size:94% position:6%
be compensated or recognized
properly, you know,

00:23:35.713 --> 00:23:38.316
for their work.

00:23:38.349 --> 00:23:46.491
And the second point I wanna
make--the second point I wanna

00:23:46.524 --> 00:23:51.362 align:start size:97% position:3%
make--want to make about
this is that the valuation of

00:23:51.395 --> 00:23:57.235 align:start position:0%
accessibility work, often it can
be--it can co-exist alongside

00:23:57.268 --> 00:24:02.540 align:start size:94% position:6%
this phenomenon of being
siloed into an accessibility

00:24:02.573 --> 00:24:05.510
maintenance role,
even, you know,

00:24:05.543 --> 00:24:09.113 align:start size:88% position:13%
when the job description
doesn't call for it.

00:24:09.146 --> 00:24:14.185 align:start position:0%
And sort of, by this, I mean
that accessibility work requires

00:24:14.218 --> 00:24:17.555 align:start size:94% position:6%
a flexibility as I mentioned
earlier with, you know,

00:24:17.588 --> 00:24:21.659 align:start size:97% position:3%
compliance culture,
accessibility in my view is a

00:24:21.692 --> 00:24:25.463 align:start size:84% position:16%
continuous, you
know, ongoing process.

00:24:25.496 --> 00:24:28.733
So when it's viewed through
a lens of, you know, being

00:24:28.766 --> 00:24:34.806 align:start position:0%
optional or not as valued,
that really puts a strain on the

00:24:34.839 --> 00:24:39.077 align:start position:0%
whole process because it doesn't
necessarily give the space

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:44.349 align:start size:94% position:6%
that's needed for digital
accessibility to really, you

00:24:44.382 --> 00:24:48.653
know, prosper and be successful.

00:24:48.686 --> 00:24:53.825 align:start position:0%
So returning to the example
presented earlier, the way this

00:24:53.858 --> 00:24:58.730
issue of value presents itself
is through the following quote

00:24:58.763 --> 00:25:03.301
on the screen, which says, "A
manager from a different team

00:25:03.334 --> 00:25:07.171 align:start size:91% position:9%
knows that you know a
lot about accessibility."

00:25:07.204 --> 00:25:12.010
So, reflecting on this for a
moment, the way the social norm

00:25:12.043 --> 00:25:20.451
manifested in this scenario is
that, you know, it's not clear

00:25:20.484 --> 00:25:24.222 align:start size:97% position:3%
from this scenario that
accessibility is considered a

00:25:24.255 --> 00:25:27.525 align:start position:0%
part of this, you know,
person's usual accessibilities.

00:25:27.558 --> 00:25:31.029
It's noted that the person is
knowledgeable; however, you

00:25:31.062 --> 00:25:35.166
know, it's also noted that they
are primarily a product designer

00:25:35.199 --> 00:25:41.539
so you can kind of assume that
they, you know, their whole job

00:25:41.572 --> 00:25:45.410 align:start size:97% position:3%
isn't focused on accessibility
which, you know, presents a

00:25:45.443 --> 00:25:50.815
different scenario but it's not
clear--the main point I'm trying

00:25:50.848 --> 00:25:54.485
to make here is it's not clear
whether this person is going to

00:25:54.518 --> 00:25:58.389 align:start size:84% position:16%
be compensated
for their time working

00:25:58.422 --> 00:26:00.258
on this accessibility process.

00:26:00.291 --> 00:26:06.698 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's sort of presented as a
favor as opposed to, you know,

00:26:06.731 --> 00:26:11.336 align:start position:0%
you're gonna get, you know,
recognition for your work, which

00:26:11.369 --> 00:26:14.539 align:start size:94% position:6%
is really, really
important in terms of value.

00:26:14.572 --> 00:26:18.543
And then, the other point I
wanna mention which is not

00:26:18.576 --> 00:26:23.448
specifically mentioned in the
slide but the general attitude,

00:26:23.481 --> 00:26:29.487
sort of, of this manager kind
of signals to me a lack of, you

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:33.358 align:start position:0%
know, recognition for the
accessibility process as, again,

00:26:33.391 --> 00:26:37.629 align:start size:94% position:6%
being, you know, continuous
process that should be

00:26:37.662 --> 00:26:44.068
incorporated from the very
beginning when possible.

00:26:44.101 --> 00:26:49.707 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, this sort of leads to
the question of why do these

00:26:49.740 --> 00:26:53.344 align:start size:91% position:9%
valuation challenges
exist in the first place.

00:26:53.377 --> 00:27:00.184
Well, in my opinion, the answer
is quite complicated, so it--I'd

00:27:00.217 --> 00:27:03.988
argue that there are a lot of
parallels that exist, you know,

00:27:04.021 --> 00:27:07.692 align:start size:97% position:3%
with the broader disability
rights movement and, you know,

00:27:07.725 --> 00:27:08.926
I'm looking at the time.

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:12.797
For sake of time, it's sort of
hard to dive into that now, but

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:15.500
if you wanna talk more about
that, definitely send me an

00:27:15.533 --> 00:27:20.304 align:start position:0%
email and I'd love to talk about
it but, essentially, the, you

00:27:20.337 --> 00:27:29.480 align:start position:0%
know, the main relationship
here is that I'd argue that the

00:27:29.513 --> 00:27:35.319
struggle with value is part of a
overarching, you know, broader

00:27:35.352 --> 00:27:39.190
perspective that exists in
the technology industry where

00:27:39.223 --> 00:27:43.461
stakeholders don't necessarily
recognize accessibility work

00:27:43.494 --> 00:27:45.697 align:start size:84% position:16%
with the value
of other disciplines,

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:48.366
other technical skills.

00:27:48.399 --> 00:27:55.707 align:start position:0%
And, you know, this is a problem
because, you know, this can

00:27:55.740 --> 00:27:58.643 align:start size:97% position:3%
manifest in different ways
where, you know, maybe someone

00:27:58.676 --> 00:28:02.413 align:start position:0%
doesn't get promoted or
recognized in the same way that,

00:28:02.446 --> 00:28:07.118
you know, other people do
because if, you know, the

00:28:07.151 --> 00:28:11.155 align:start position:0%
employers don't recognize, okay,
accessibility work, it's very

00:28:11.188 --> 00:28:16.127 align:start position:0%
significant, it's important, and
it's, you know, critical to a

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:23.301
product having a strong useable
experience that, you know, that

00:28:23.334 --> 00:28:25.036
can create significant problems.

00:28:25.069 --> 00:28:32.643 align:start position:0%
And then the second part of
this where, you know, sometimes

00:28:32.676 --> 00:28:35.780
accessibility can sort of be
viewed through this lens of

00:28:35.813 --> 00:28:40.551 align:start position:0%
volunteering where, as I
mentioned earlier, it's unclear

00:28:40.584 --> 00:28:43.721 align:start position:0%
whether this person in this
scenario is going to be properly

00:28:43.754 --> 00:28:49.026
compensated for their time and,
if this is just a favor, you

00:28:49.059 --> 00:28:54.699
know, that doesn't really--that
doesn't really, you know, help

00:28:54.732 --> 00:28:58.469 align:start size:91% position:9%
with accessibility
being properly recognized.

00:28:58.502 --> 00:29:02.440 align:start position:0%
And last point I wanna make
about this before moving to the

00:29:02.473 --> 00:29:07.078 align:start size:97% position:3%
next social norm is I
personally struggle with this.

00:29:07.111 --> 00:29:10.782
You know, and maybe people
tuning in as well really

00:29:10.815 --> 00:29:14.085
struggle because as someone
who's really passionate about

00:29:14.118 --> 00:29:18.089
digital accessibility, I'm so,
you know, I'm really happy when

00:29:18.122 --> 00:29:22.093 align:start size:97% position:3%
people, you know, express
interest in it, even if it is

00:29:22.126 --> 00:29:27.999
last-minute or, you know,
even if it is challenging.

00:29:28.032 --> 00:29:32.170 align:start size:97% position:3%
So I'm definitely more, you
know, inclined to I wanna help

00:29:32.203 --> 00:29:38.009
as much as I can but that can
also present a challenge when,

00:29:38.042 --> 00:29:42.713 align:start position:0%
even if I help, if my, you know,
work isn't valued in the same

00:29:42.746 --> 00:29:47.018 align:start size:78% position:22%
way, it can be
quite frustrating.

00:29:47.051 --> 00:29:54.292
So, on that note, moving to the
third and final social norm that

00:29:54.325 --> 00:29:59.397
I'm going to discuss today,
is the specific attitudes and

00:29:59.430 --> 00:30:03.467 align:start position:0%
behaviors that people face when,
you know, first entering the

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:08.206 align:start position:0%
field of digital accessibility,
specifically in relation to

00:30:08.239 --> 00:30:15.113 align:start size:91% position:9%
educational opportunities
for accessibility.

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:20.818
Okay, so a recurring theme with
that, the offerings for digital

00:30:20.851 --> 00:30:25.156
accessibility education are
not particularly robust in

00:30:25.189 --> 00:30:30.361
comparison to other skills, you
know, other technical skills

00:30:30.394 --> 00:30:32.496
in design and development.

00:30:32.529 --> 00:30:38.669
And the repercussions for these
lack of accessibility resources

00:30:38.702 --> 00:30:44.842
is, you know, widespread and I
kind of wanna, you know, focus

00:30:44.875 --> 00:30:49.680
this section on a couple of key
points but, you know, one of the

00:30:49.713 --> 00:30:54.785
points I have listed onscreen is
that there is no, you know, one

00:30:54.818 --> 00:30:58.222 align:start position:0%
pathway to studying digital
accessibility, which on the one

00:30:58.255 --> 00:31:04.128
hand is good because, you know,
I, you know, personally relate

00:31:04.161 --> 00:31:08.399 align:start position:0%
to this idea that I have
picked up lessons about digital

00:31:08.432 --> 00:31:13.804
accessibility on the job which
helps in terms of, you know,

00:31:13.837 --> 00:31:18.376
learning practical ways to apply
accessibility but, at the same

00:31:18.409 --> 00:31:22.046 align:start size:94% position:6%
time, you know, if one
doesn't have access to work

00:31:22.079 --> 00:31:28.519
opportunities, to learn, it can
make things quite difficult to

00:31:28.552 --> 00:31:34.492
gather digital accessibility,
you know, specific practices,

00:31:34.525 --> 00:31:39.497 align:start position:0%
which leads to kind of the third
point I have here, which is

00:31:39.530 --> 00:31:44.869
there is, I have found, as well
as in my research, that there

00:31:44.902 --> 00:31:48.506 align:start position:0%
are pretty significant
differences that exist between,

00:31:48.539 --> 00:31:51.676
you know, learning about
accessibility from this

00:31:51.709 --> 00:31:57.114
theoretical perspective
versus implementing it.

00:31:57.147 --> 00:32:00.318
And, you know, there are lots
of, I was, before moving, I did

00:32:00.351 --> 00:32:05.189
wanna mention, you know, there
are lots of great resources and

00:32:05.222 --> 00:32:11.462
classes out there and, you know,
if you have any favorite classes

00:32:11.495 --> 00:32:15.499
or things I would love to, you
know, see them in the comments.

00:32:15.532 --> 00:32:22.673 align:start size:94% position:6%
But I wanted to note, you
know, in terms of mainstream

00:32:22.706 --> 00:32:27.511
educational options, you know, I
would say there are not any, you

00:32:27.544 --> 00:32:31.716 align:start position:0%
know, major degrees that specify
in digital accessibility.

00:32:31.749 --> 00:32:37.088
There are minor certificates,
you know, online classes which

00:32:37.121 --> 00:32:41.659
are great, but I, you know, I
think if, for example, if there

00:32:41.692 --> 00:32:46.197 align:start position:0%
was a master's degree in digital
accessibility I would totally

00:32:46.230 --> 00:32:53.070 align:start position:0%
want to enroll in that, but from
my search, there is not, and

00:32:53.103 --> 00:32:58.776
that can, you know, that is sort
of a challenge in and of itself

00:32:58.809 --> 00:33:02.313
because, you know, stakeholders
at universities and educational

00:33:02.346 --> 00:33:07.618 align:start position:0%
programs do not always recognize
accessibility work with the

00:33:07.651 --> 00:33:09.720
value of other disciplines.

00:33:09.753 --> 00:33:15.192 align:start position:0%
So one way this manifests
specifically is, you know, from

00:33:15.225 --> 00:33:19.163 align:start position:0%
people I've talked to,
accessibility can, you know, be

00:33:19.196 --> 00:33:23.401
incorporated into computer
science classes or sometimes

00:33:23.434 --> 00:33:26.504 align:start position:0%
even have a whole course
dedicated to accessibility which

00:33:26.537 --> 00:33:35.646 align:start position:0%
is great, but I feel like and--I
feel like this is a common

00:33:35.679 --> 00:33:40.084
feeling but accessibility is so
expansive and, like I mentioned

00:33:40.117 --> 00:33:48.159
in the previous slide, it's hard
to sort of narrow it down versus

00:33:48.192 --> 00:33:51.562
into, you know, theory versus
practice, so I feel like if

00:33:51.595 --> 00:33:54.832 align:start size:94% position:6%
there was more room and
more recognition of digital

00:33:54.865 --> 00:33:59.837 align:start size:97% position:3%
accessibility in these
mainstream educational places

00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:04.508
and spaces, I should say,
that, you know, would lead

00:34:04.541 --> 00:34:08.446
to more widespread education.

00:34:08.479 --> 00:34:13.717 align:start size:97% position:3%
Okay, so through this example,
I--the social norm sort of

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:17.721 align:start position:0%
manifested through the quote,
"You primarily work as a product

00:34:17.754 --> 00:34:21.725
designer, but you're considered
the," quote, "'go-to' person for

00:34:21.758 --> 00:34:24.295 align:start size:84% position:16%
digital accessibility
in the company."

00:34:24.328 --> 00:34:28.632
So, solely from what I've
gathered, particularly at

00:34:28.665 --> 00:34:34.305
smaller companies and startups,
it's sort of not uncommon for

00:34:34.338 --> 00:34:37.475 align:start size:94% position:6%
there to be sort of this,
you know, "go-to" person for

00:34:37.508 --> 00:34:44.181
accessibility, you know, which
is fine but I think, you know, I

00:34:44.214 --> 00:34:47.318 align:start size:97% position:3%
think in an ideal world, it
would be amazing if, you know,

00:34:47.351 --> 00:34:50.721
every person had at least a
foundation in accessibility

00:34:50.754 --> 00:34:54.725 align:start position:0%
because, you know, accessibility
doesn't exist in this vacuum.

00:34:54.758 --> 00:34:57.828
It's not just, you know, an
engineering concern, design

00:34:57.861 --> 00:35:04.001
concern, content concern, you
know, a recruiting concern.

00:35:04.034 --> 00:35:09.306 align:start size:97% position:3%
You know, it really exists
widespread so I think it's not

00:35:09.339 --> 00:35:14.044
particularly fair for the, you
know, responsibility to be with

00:35:14.077 --> 00:35:21.318 align:start position:0%
one person so sort of one way
to combat this is for, you know,

00:35:21.351 --> 00:35:28.826
education to be more widespread
and at the university training

00:35:28.859 --> 00:35:31.729
crash course level,
accessibility, more

00:35:31.762 --> 00:35:33.497 align:start size:88% position:13%
accessibility
knowledge would be good.

00:35:33.530 --> 00:35:39.136 align:start position:0%
But employers can also, you
know, have a role in this when,

00:35:39.169 --> 00:35:44.308 align:start position:0%
you know, when new employees
are being onboarded, be great if

00:35:44.341 --> 00:35:49.647 align:start position:0%
accessibility is discussed
and, you know, acknowledged and

00:35:49.680 --> 00:35:53.050
specific practices for
that company are shared.

00:35:53.083 --> 00:35:58.822 align:start size:84% position:16%
So it's not sort of
reliant on one person.

00:35:58.855 --> 00:36:03.260
Okay, so wrapping up, we're
about 35 minutes so I think

00:36:03.293 --> 00:36:07.097
about 5 to 10 more minutes
and then I'd love to take any

00:36:07.130 --> 00:36:08.265
questions for a bit.

00:36:08.298 --> 00:36:12.503 align:start size:97% position:3%
But the first future direction
is, I think it's really

00:36:12.536 --> 00:36:18.609
important for people working in
digital accessibility to work

00:36:18.642 --> 00:36:22.780 align:start size:97% position:3%
towards combating solutionism,
so I should say here,

00:36:22.813 --> 00:36:29.653 align:start position:0%
solutionism is sort of a concept
designed by this theorist,

00:36:29.686 --> 00:36:36.794 align:start position:0%
Morozov, who I cite more in
the references but, essentially,

00:36:36.827 --> 00:36:42.032 align:start position:0%
solutionism is this idea
that there is a goal of solving

00:36:42.065 --> 00:36:46.637
problems, as opposed to, you
know, actually addressing the

00:36:46.670 --> 00:36:49.406 align:start size:81% position:19%
complexity of
problems that exist

00:36:49.439 --> 00:36:51.141
in the technology industry.

00:36:51.174 --> 00:36:54.478 align:start size:91% position:9%
And I think this is
quite relevant to digital

00:36:54.511 --> 00:36:59.149 align:start position:0%
accessibility because, you know,
digital accessibility, as I

00:36:59.182 --> 00:37:01.452
mentioned, you know,
it's quite complex.

00:37:01.485 --> 00:37:05.422 align:start position:0%
Not only is it an ongoing
process but it's very widespread

00:37:05.455 --> 00:37:10.261 align:start size:97% position:3%
and interdisciplinary, so it's
critical that it's viewed

00:37:10.294 --> 00:37:11.495
in that light.

00:37:11.529 --> 00:37:15.699 align:start position:0%
It's not just, you know, ticking
the specific boxes of policy,

00:37:15.732 --> 00:37:20.638
but it's recognized as a
comprehensive, you know,

00:37:20.671 --> 00:37:26.477 align:start position:0%
widespread consideration so some
concrete ways to address this

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:31.615
would be, you know, making sure
that every person in, you know,

00:37:31.648 --> 00:37:37.121
a company or a product team, is
knowledgeable about at least the

00:37:37.154 --> 00:37:42.626
basics of accessibility but
also, you know, consistently

00:37:42.659 --> 00:37:49.133 align:start position:0%
testing with users to make sure,
okay, this product, you know,

00:37:49.166 --> 00:37:52.303 align:start position:0%
testing with users with
disabilities so there's an open

00:37:52.336 --> 00:37:58.309
line of communication and that
you're recognizing that, okay,

00:37:58.342 --> 00:38:03.247
the goal is to make this a good
usability experience, not just

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:06.750 align:start size:81% position:19%
to, you know,
tick off some boxes.

00:38:06.783 --> 00:38:11.488 align:start position:0%
Then the second future direction
is there's really a critical

00:38:11.521 --> 00:38:14.758 align:start size:94% position:6%
need to increase the
value of accessibility work.

00:38:14.791 --> 00:38:18.295
And like I said earlier, this
is not, you know, there are

00:38:18.328 --> 00:38:20.664
certainly exceptions to this.

00:38:20.697 --> 00:38:24.768 align:start position:0%
However, I would say, you
know, a trend that I am kind of

00:38:24.801 --> 00:38:31.041
concerned about is, you know,
it's not always--the value of

00:38:31.074 --> 00:38:33.644
accessibility work is not
always, I think, given the

00:38:33.677 --> 00:38:35.813
recognition that it deserves.

00:38:35.846 --> 00:38:39.783
And, you know, people,
stakeholders in the tech

00:38:39.816 --> 00:38:44.521
industry, certainly play a role
in this but, you know, also, you

00:38:44.554 --> 00:38:48.292
know, anyone on a product team
just, you know, advocating for

00:38:48.325 --> 00:38:52.162 align:start position:0%
accessibility, calling out
the work, supporting, you know,

00:38:52.195 --> 00:38:56.834 align:start size:97% position:3%
people who also work in
accessibility, is, you know, a

00:38:56.867 --> 00:38:59.737
great way to address this.

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:05.142
And then, finally, which is
probably the future direction

00:39:05.175 --> 00:39:08.779
that I'm most excited about, is
this, you know, starting point

00:39:08.812 --> 00:39:13.250
that I wanna suggest is that
integrating creativity into the

00:39:13.283 --> 00:39:20.124
conversation is really a, you
know, a great way, I think, to

00:39:20.157 --> 00:39:24.294
draw greater interest
and respect of digital

00:39:24.327 --> 00:39:31.268
accessibility--greater
interest and respect

00:39:31.301 --> 00:39:33.604
in the technology industry.

00:39:33.637 --> 00:39:41.111
And, you know, there are a lot
of great projects in this space

00:39:41.144 --> 00:39:46.450
which, you know, I can also
share links to if you wanna

00:39:46.483 --> 00:39:47.684
email me afterwards.

00:39:47.718 --> 00:39:54.391
But essentially, creativity is,
you know, a great vehicle for,

00:39:54.424 --> 00:39:56.794 align:start size:94% position:6%
you know,
approaching digital access.

00:39:56.827 --> 00:40:01.732
And sort of to, you know, wrap
up, I wanted to say, you know,

00:40:01.765 --> 00:40:05.636 align:start size:88% position:13%
stakeholder changes
are, you know, critical.

00:40:05.669 --> 00:40:09.740
Creative approaches are great,
and then collaboration in the

00:40:09.773 --> 00:40:14.478 align:start position:0%
accessibility community is also,
you know, really important,

00:40:14.511 --> 00:40:19.149
which is why, you know, events
like this are really exciting

00:40:19.182 --> 00:40:23.253 align:start size:94% position:6%
and, you know, I'm really
excited to be a part of this

00:40:23.286 --> 00:40:27.157
and, you know, connect and, you
know, virtually meet people who

00:40:27.190 --> 00:40:31.528 align:start size:97% position:3%
also really care about
digital access, so that's it.

00:40:31.561 --> 00:40:33.764
These are my references.

00:40:33.797 --> 00:40:38.836
The slides are available at the
Wordpress Accessibility site if

00:40:38.869 --> 00:40:41.538
you wanna, you know, go
through the references.

00:40:41.571 --> 00:40:43.574
You can also send me an email.

00:40:43.607 --> 00:40:47.177 align:start size:84% position:16%
My email's
dana.frayne@gmail.com,

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:50.781 align:start size:91% position:9%
and also my Twitter handle
is dana_frayne.

00:40:50.814 --> 00:40:53.851
I just want to thank quickly,
you know, Joe Dolson and the

00:40:53.884 --> 00:40:58.121 align:start position:0%
whole Wordpress Accessibility
team for having me and I'm happy

00:40:58.154 --> 00:41:00.023
to take any questions.

00:41:00.056 --> 00:41:01.625 align:start size:88% position:13%
female: Well,
thank you so much, Dana.

00:41:01.658 --> 00:41:03.160 align:start size:81% position:19%
We do have a
couple of questions.

00:41:03.193 --> 00:41:06.063
The first one is: "Do you
consider that the multiple

00:41:06.096 --> 00:41:10.033
truths viewpoint is reflected in
the fact that there's frequently

00:41:10.066 --> 00:41:16.073
no one true solution to web
accessibility questions?"

00:41:16.106 --> 00:41:17.508
Dana: That's a
great question.

00:41:17.541 --> 00:41:23.647 align:start position:0%
So it is something that I,
you know, think about because I

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:27.684
totally, you know, align
with this idea that digital

00:41:27.717 --> 00:41:33.090
accessibility is a fluid social
construction and, by that, I

00:41:33.123 --> 00:41:37.094
mean, you know, accessibility
means something different, I

00:41:37.127 --> 00:41:38.829
think, to each person.

00:41:38.862 --> 00:41:45.369 align:start position:0%
So I really, you know, hesitate,
kind of, when, you know,

00:41:45.402 --> 00:41:50.173
accessibility is defined
as, you know, X, Y, and Z.

00:41:50.206 --> 00:41:55.846
I think it really is dependent
on local context and, you know,

00:41:55.879 --> 00:41:59.416 align:start position:0%
again tying back to this concept
of intersectionality, it's

00:41:59.449 --> 00:42:04.721
really important I think to
acknowledge that, you know,

00:42:04.754 --> 00:42:06.790
accessibility doesn't
exist in a vacuum.

00:42:06.823 --> 00:42:11.128 align:start size:97% position:3%
It sort of touches on
these different dimensions of

00:42:11.161 --> 00:42:15.632
identity, so I certainly think
that there's a connection there

00:42:15.665 --> 00:42:22.472 align:start position:0%
and thanks for pointing that
out for who asked that question.

00:42:22.505 --> 00:42:24.808
female: So the next question
is "What would you like to see

00:42:24.841 --> 00:42:26.310
done with your research?

00:42:26.343 --> 00:42:29.813
Do you have goals for it?"

00:42:29.846 --> 00:42:32.182 align:start size:88% position:13%
Dana: Yes, this is
another great question.

00:42:32.215 --> 00:42:37.688
I mean, I think, hopefully, I,
you know, would love to publish

00:42:37.721 --> 00:42:42.826 align:start position:0%
my research in a academic
article but, you know, that is a

00:42:42.859 --> 00:42:46.563 align:start size:97% position:3%
pretty intense process, but I,
you know, it's something

00:42:46.596 --> 00:42:49.333
that I hope to do.

00:42:49.366 --> 00:42:55.505
And also next year, I hope to,
you know, fingers crossed, I'll

00:42:55.538 --> 00:43:00.544
be able to go to Morocco with
the Fulbright program to do a

00:43:00.577 --> 00:43:05.449
research grant where I can sort
of continue this research and,

00:43:05.482 --> 00:43:11.521
you know, approach it from a
different lens of studying

00:43:11.554 --> 00:43:17.127
digital accessibility within a
specific context, as opposed to,

00:43:17.160 --> 00:43:18.629
you know, this research today.

00:43:18.662 --> 00:43:23.200
I recognize that it's, you know,
quite broad, so I think it would

00:43:23.233 --> 00:43:26.637 align:start position:0%
be exciting to sort of go at it
from a different angle

00:43:26.670 --> 00:43:29.806
and be more specific.

00:43:29.839 --> 00:43:31.675
female: Do you--are you
hoping that it'll inspire

00:43:31.708 --> 00:43:36.179 align:start position:0%
certain actions either at the
government level or among people

00:43:36.212 --> 00:43:40.484 align:start position:0%
who work in digital
accessibility on a daily basis?

00:43:40.517 --> 00:43:43.086
Dana: Sorry, can you
repeat that real quick?

00:43:43.119 --> 00:43:45.188 align:start size:97% position:3%
female: Oh, I was just
following up on that question.

00:43:45.221 --> 00:43:47.758 align:start size:97% position:3%
Are you hoping that your
research would inspire certain

00:43:47.791 --> 00:43:52.496
actions either at the government
level or with those of us that

00:43:52.529 --> 00:43:55.165 align:start size:84% position:16%
work in accessibility
on a daily basis?

00:43:55.198 --> 00:43:56.500
Dana: Well, sure, yeah.

00:43:56.533 --> 00:43:58.835 align:start size:81% position:19%
I mean, I think
that would be great.

00:43:58.868 --> 00:44:04.141 align:start size:97% position:3%
You know, I think the one,
you know, main takeaway that I

00:44:04.174 --> 00:44:09.379 align:start position:0%
really hope my research can
share is that I think, you know,

00:44:09.412 --> 00:44:12.015 align:start position:0%
my personal experience
working in digital accessibility

00:44:12.048 --> 00:44:18.655 align:start position:0%
sometimes it can feel, you know,
a bit, you know, lonely if,

00:44:18.688 --> 00:44:21.525
you know, going back to that
scenario where there's one

00:44:21.558 --> 00:44:24.528 align:start size:94% position:6%
person on this team
who's considered the expert.

00:44:24.561 --> 00:44:28.632
I feel like, you know, when I
was conducting this research I

00:44:28.665 --> 00:44:31.735
think it made me feel quite an
appreciation for the community

00:44:31.768 --> 00:44:36.239
and, you know, knowing that
there are lots of people all

00:44:36.272 --> 00:44:39.476
over the world who really care
about digital accessibility and,

00:44:39.509 --> 00:44:42.179
if you're working on this
project, you know, you're

00:44:42.212 --> 00:44:45.315 align:start size:94% position:6%
not--if you experience
something, there's probably

00:44:45.348 --> 00:44:49.086 align:start size:97% position:3%
someone somewhere who is
experiencing something similar

00:44:49.119 --> 00:44:54.391
so if you can sort of find, you
know, reach out to the community

00:44:54.424 --> 00:45:00.997 align:start position:0%
and, you know, make connections
and feel the sense of

00:45:01.030 --> 00:45:03.667 align:start size:88% position:13%
camaraderie, I think
that would be something.

00:45:03.700 --> 00:45:08.004
I hope that is inspired
through this research.

00:45:08.037 --> 00:45:09.673 align:start size:94% position:6%
female: Yeah, no, that
is definitely something with

00:45:09.706 --> 00:45:11.174
Wordpress, right?

00:45:11.207 --> 00:45:13.443
And accessibility as well.

00:45:13.476 --> 00:45:17.047 align:start size:88% position:13%
We're very big on
community building, so.

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:20.117 align:start position:0%
There's a question here: "Do
you have ideas about ways to get

00:45:20.150 --> 00:45:22.452
people excited about
the creative aspects of

00:45:22.485 --> 00:45:26.523 align:start position:0%
accessibility instead of viewing
it as a maintenance task?

00:45:26.556 --> 00:45:28.024
Dana: Yes, certainly.

00:45:28.057 --> 00:45:33.163 align:start size:94% position:6%
I mean, I think--let's
see, how to structure this.

00:45:33.196 --> 00:45:38.068
Well, you know, one example that
I wanna, you know, I think would

00:45:38.101 --> 00:45:41.204 align:start position:0%
be great to draw attention to is
there is this project called

00:45:41.237 --> 00:45:44.474
Alt Text as Poetry.

00:45:44.507 --> 00:45:52.249
And I, you know, the specific
authors kind of, I can't recall

00:45:52.282 --> 00:45:55.819
them off the top of my head but
hopefully, I can, you know, add

00:45:55.852 --> 00:45:59.322
them in the--add a
link in the chat.

00:45:59.355 --> 00:46:00.590
female: Shannon Finnigan?

00:46:00.623 --> 00:46:02.793
Dana: Yes, yeah, yeah.

00:46:02.826 --> 00:46:08.031
And then, so I think this is,
you know, a really brilliant

00:46:08.064 --> 00:46:17.307
project because the, you know,
they really exemplify how, you

00:46:17.340 --> 00:46:21.311
know, alt text is can--you know,
some people can view it as, you

00:46:21.344 --> 00:46:26.283
know, the static, rigid practice
but it's, in a way, I feel like

00:46:26.316 --> 00:46:29.452
it is sort of a poetic form,
and they really, you know,

00:46:29.485 --> 00:46:32.689 align:start size:94% position:6%
encapsulate that and I think
projects like that

00:46:32.722 --> 00:46:34.724
are really exciting.

00:46:34.757 --> 00:46:39.563
I know there's also, you know, a
movement in the 'zine world to

00:46:39.596 --> 00:46:43.366 align:start size:97% position:3%
sort of push for digital
accessibility and sort of, you

00:46:43.399 --> 00:46:47.070 align:start position:0%
know, when there are artistic
projects like that, that I think

00:46:47.103 --> 00:46:52.742
that can be really exciting, and
it's something that excites me.

00:46:52.775 --> 00:46:55.078
female: Yeah, I think we have
time for one more question

00:46:55.111 --> 00:46:58.181
and it's actually my question.

00:46:58.214 --> 00:47:02.085 align:start position:0%
I'm wondering how do you propose
to increase the valuation of

00:47:02.118 --> 00:47:06.022
digital accessibility so, you
know, we see a lot of almost

00:47:06.055 --> 00:47:10.794
like fear-based arguments for
accessibility and I'm wondering

00:47:10.827 --> 00:47:15.432
if you have thoughts on ways to
increase that valuation that's

00:47:15.465 --> 00:47:18.034
maybe not fear-based, or do
you feel like, looking at the

00:47:18.067 --> 00:47:21.338
social, that that is
just the way to go?

00:47:21.371 --> 00:47:23.306 align:start size:97% position:3%
Dana: That's my--I
mean, that's a great question.

00:47:23.339 --> 00:47:27.344
I feel like it's something I
sort of debate internally as

00:47:27.377 --> 00:47:32.782 align:start position:0%
well because, I mean, I think
we do live in sort of a call-out

00:47:32.815 --> 00:47:38.555
culture where fear is sort
of--can be a driving force.

00:47:38.588 --> 00:47:42.659 align:start size:94% position:6%
However, I think, you know,
that's not the only way

00:47:42.692 --> 00:47:43.893
to go about it.

00:47:43.927 --> 00:47:48.064
I think, you know, grassroots
activism and sort of going back

